{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509285"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:15:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:15:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11412"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11412"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.04,0.08,0.7,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4048"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79165"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4048"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11412"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64517"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4650"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6385"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26996"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42596"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79165"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents with a 4-month history of a \u2018pounding heart\u2019. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer past medical history includes hypertension for which she takes ramipril. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs part of her workup, laboratory tests including a full blood count with differential, renal function and electrolytes, and thyroid function tests are performed, which are all within normal limits. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer ECG is shown below (Image). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA follow-up echocardiogram is undertaken which is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most appropriate form of long-term anticoagulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aspirin and clopidogrel","Enoxaparin","Warfarin","Apixaban","No anticoagulation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG shown above is consistent with atrial fibrillation (irregularly irregular rhythm, absent p waves, fibrillatory waves). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs this woman has a CHA2DS2-VASc of 3 (age 65-74, female and hypertension), the benefits of long-term anticoagulation would outweigh the risks, hence \u003Cstrong\u003Eno anticoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Ewarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E has been the traditional choice for long-term anticoagulation in atrial fibrillation, best practice has now shifted toward the use of the direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs) such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eapixaban\u003C/strong\u003E for non-valvular AF in patients with normal renal function, which avoid the necessity of blood tests to monitor INRs. However, DOACs are an inappropriate option for patients with valvular-AF or significant renal impairment (eGFR\u0026lt; 15 for apixaban/rivaroxaban). The ARISTOTLE trial (2011) demonstrated that apixaban 5 mg BD was superior to warfarin in prevention of stroke or systemic embolism in non-valvular AF as well as associated with lower rates of major bleeding and haemorrhagic stroke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E is not used anticoagulation long term as it must be given subcutaneously, and patients generally prefer oral tablets for convenience. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin and clopidogrel \u003C/strong\u003Eare antiplatelet agents and do not have an anticoagulant effect. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A DOAC, such as apixaban, is the preferred anticoagulant for patients with atrial fibrillation.","The CHA2DS2-VASc score is used to assess stroke risk in patients with atrial fibrillation and guide anticoagulation decisions."],"references":["Granger CB, Alexander JH, McMurray JJ, Lopes RD, Hylek EM, Hanna M, Al-Khalidi HR, Ansell J, Atar D, Avezum A, Bahit MC, Diaz R, Easton JD, Ezekowitz JA, Flaker G, Garcia D, Geraldes M, Gersh BJ, Golitsyn S, Goto S, Hermosillo AG, Hohnloser SH, Horowitz J, Mohan P, Jansky P, Lewis BS, Lopez-Sendon JL, Pais P, Parkhomenko A, Verheugt FW, Zhu J, Wallentin L; ARISTOTLE Committees and Investigators. Apixaban versus warfarin in patients with atrial fibrillation. N Engl J Med. 2011 Sep 15;365(11):981-92. doi: 10.1056/NEJMoa1107039. Epub 2011 Aug 27. PMID: 21870978. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21870978/","Guenoun M, Cohen S, Villaceque M, Sharareh A, Schwartz J, Hoffman O, Dib JC, Ouazana L, Assouline S, Parrens E, Garban T, Pradeau V, Guedj-Meynier D, Lequeux B, Cohen C, Durand P, Dievart F, Dhanjal TS, Sabouret P, Lellouche N. Characteristics of patients with atrial fibrillation treated with direct oral anticoagulants and new insights into inappropriate dosing: results from the French National Prospective Registry: PAFF. Europace. 2023 Oct 5;25(10):euad302. doi: 10.1093/europace/euad302. PMID: 37801642; PMCID: PMC10590101. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37801642/","Steffel J, Collins R, Antz M, Cornu P, Desteghe L, Haeusler KG, Oldgren J, Reinecke H, Roldan-Schilling V, Rowell N, Sinnaeve P, Vanassche T, Potpara T, Camm AJ, Heidb\u00fcchel H; External reviewers. 2021 European Heart Rhythm Association Practical Guide on the Use of Non-Vitamin K Antagonist Oral Anticoagulants in Patients with Atrial Fibrillation. Europace. 2021 Oct 9;23(10):1612-1676. doi: 10.1093/europace/euab065. Erratum in: Europace. 2021 Oct 9;23(10):1676. doi: 10.1093/europace/euab157. PMID: 33895845; PMCID: PMC11636576. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33895845/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64517"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11412"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19824"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19824"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/017eae1b-5664-45c6-9c39-bf2a001e1ff3.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/017eae1b-5664-45c6-9c39-bf2a001e1ff3.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":418}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64517"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T15:54:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T15:55:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4048"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79165"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships